1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:02.378
Everyone keeps saying AI is jagged.

2
00:00:02.378 --> 00:00:04.980
Good at some things, terrible at others.

3
00:00:04.980 --> 00:00:08.039
It's the organizing frame for how we deploy AI,

4
00:00:08.039 --> 00:00:09.080
how we teach it,

5
00:00:09.080 --> 00:00:11.292
how we think about what it can and

6
00:00:11.292 --> 00:00:11.878
can't do.

7
00:00:11.878 --> 00:00:15.002
But what if jagged isn't the right word anymore?

8
00:00:15.002 --> 00:00:16.238
Jake's Daily Build.

9
00:00:16.238 --> 00:00:17.149
What we built.

10
00:00:17.149 --> 00:00:17.865
What broke.

11
00:00:17.865 --> 00:00:18.841
What I learned.

12
00:00:18.841 --> 00:00:23.136
Four companies built the same thing without talking to each other.

13
00:00:23.136 --> 00:00:25.608
Anthropic, Google, OpenAI, and Cursor.

14
00:00:25.608 --> 00:00:29.708
All four arrived at the same architecture: decompose a problem,

15
00:00:29.708 --> 00:00:31.986
parallelize the work across agents,

16
00:00:31.986 --> 00:00:32.962
verify outputs,

17
00:00:32.962 --> 00:00:34.198
iterate until done.

18
00:00:34.198 --> 00:00:36.541
Cursor is the most interesting case.

19
00:00:36.541 --> 00:00:38.363
They built a coding harness.

20
00:00:38.363 --> 00:00:39.794
Planners create tasks,

21
00:00:39.794 --> 00:00:42.397
workers grind through them in isolation,

22
00:00:42.397 --> 00:00:42.592
and

23
00:00:42.592 --> 00:00:46.041
a judge decides whether to continue or restart fresh.

24
00:00:46.041 --> 00:00:49.230
They used it to build a web browser from scratch.

25
00:00:49.230 --> 00:00:50.791
A million lines of Rust.

26
00:00:50.791 --> 00:00:55.737
Then they pointed that same coding harness at a research-grade math problem.

27
00:00:55.737 --> 00:00:59.771
Spectral graph theory, from unpublished Stanford and MIT work.

28
00:00:59.771 --> 00:01:02.700
The system ran for four days with zero hints.

29
00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:06.214
And it found a better solution than the human authors.

30
00:01:06.214 --> 00:01:07.190
A coding agent.

31
00:01:07.190 --> 00:01:09.728
Solving math it was never designed for.

32
00:01:09.728 --> 00:01:11.810
Because the harness generalizes.

33
00:01:11.810 --> 00:01:14.152
I mapped Renky against this pattern.

34
00:01:14.152 --> 00:01:15.584
Here's where we stand.

35
00:01:15.584 --> 00:01:20.595
Decompose: we have plans, phases, and sub-agents that break work into pieces.

36
00:01:20.595 --> 00:01:22.091
Score: seventy percent.

37
00:01:22.091 --> 00:01:23.913
We don't auto-decompose yet.

38
00:01:23.913 --> 00:01:26.516
Parallelize: we have worktree isolation.

39
00:01:26.516 --> 00:01:29.054
Each sub-agent gets its own git branch.

40
00:01:29.054 --> 00:01:30.421
Score: sixty percent.

41
00:01:30.421 --> 00:01:31.527
No batch fan-out.

42
00:01:31.527 --> 00:01:34.455
Verify: babysitter with ten automated checks,

43
00:01:34.455 --> 00:01:37.644
action verifier that catches hallucinated claims,

44
00:01:37.644 --> 00:01:40.897
a skill test framework with behavioral assertions,

45
00:01:40.897 --> 00:01:41.092
and

46
00:01:41.092 --> 00:01:42.849
automatic retry on failure.

47
00:01:42.849 --> 00:01:44.606
Score: ninety-five percent.

48
00:01:44.606 --> 00:01:47.990
Iterate: phase runner clears context between phases,

49
00:01:47.990 --> 00:01:50.007
WORKON dot MD handles handoffs,

50
00:01:50.007 --> 00:01:52.740
Cortex persists knowledge across sessions.

51
00:01:52.740 --> 00:01:54.172
Score: ninety percent.

52
00:01:54.172 --> 00:01:55.669
The gap is one feature.

53
00:01:55.669 --> 00:01:56.580
Batch fan-out.

54
00:01:56.580 --> 00:02:01.590
Take a big task, auto-split it into parallel worktree workers, merge results.

55
00:02:01.590 --> 00:02:04.974
That closes both the decompose and parallelize gaps.

56
00:02:04.974 --> 00:02:08.358
One feature turns Renky into a complete DPVI system.

57
00:02:08.358 --> 00:02:11.351
But here's the real takeaway from all of this.

58
00:02:11.351 --> 00:02:15.060
The reason AI looked jagged was never about intelligence.

59
00:02:15.060 --> 00:02:20.917
It was about asking a capable analyst to solve everything in thirty seconds with no notes,

60
00:02:20.917 --> 00:02:21.828
no colleagues,

61
00:02:21.828 --> 00:02:22.544
no retries.

62
00:02:22.544 --> 00:02:24.886
We gave it organizational structure.

63
00:02:24.886 --> 00:02:26.643
The jaggedness disappeared.

64
00:02:26.643 --> 00:02:29.571
Cursor's key finding makes this even clearer.

65
00:02:29.571 --> 00:02:33.606
The improvements came from removing complexity, not adding it.

66
00:02:33.606 --> 00:02:36.014
Stripping out coordination machinery.

67
00:02:36.014 --> 00:02:37.120
Adding hierarchy.

68
00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:39.658
Letting agents work in clean isolation.

69
00:02:39.658 --> 00:02:41.675
Simple systems doing hard work.

70
00:02:41.675 --> 00:02:43.887
The frontier isn't jagged anymore.

71
00:02:43.887 --> 00:02:44.733
Not for work.

72
00:02:44.733 --> 00:02:53.063
The question isn't "can AI do my job." The question is "can my work be decomposed into verifiable steps." And the answer

73
00:02:53.063 --> 00:02:55.861
far more often than we're comfortable with.

74
00:02:55.861 --> 00:02:57.618
That's The Smooth Frontier.

75
00:02:57.618 --> 00:02:58.203
I'm Jake.

76
00:02:58.203 --> 00:02:59.700
Catch you next episode.
